hands_on_practices.solution:
The van der Waals equation of state for one mole is written in terms of molar volume $v$ as
$$
P(v,T) = \frac{R T}{v - b} - \frac{a}{v^{2}}.
$$
At the critical point, the isotherm has an inflection point, which imposes the conditions
$$
\left(\frac{\partial P}{\partial v}\right)_{T} = 0, \quad \left(\frac{\partial^{2} P}{\partial v^{2}}\right)_{T} = 0.
$$
Computing the derivatives,
$$
\frac{\partial P}{\partial v} = -\frac{R T}{(v - b)^{2}} + \frac{2 a}{v^{3}}, \quad \frac{\partial^{2} P}{\partial v^{2}} = \frac{2 R T}{(v - b)^{3}} - \frac{6 a}{v^{4}}.
$$
Setting these to zero at the critical point $(v_{c}, T_{c}, P_{c})$ gives
$$
\frac{R T_{c}}{(v_{c} - b)^{2}} = \frac{2 a}{v_{c}^{3}}, \quad \frac{R T_{c}}{(v_{c} - b)^{3}} = \frac{3 a}{v_{c}^{4}}.
$$
Dividing the second equation by the first yields
$$
\frac{1}{v_{c} - b} = \frac{3}{2} \cdot \frac{1}{v_{c}} \;\;\Rightarrow\;\; \frac{v_{c}}{v_{c} - b} = \frac{3}{2} \;\;\Rightarrow\;\; 2 v_{c} = 3(v_{c} - b) \;\;\Rightarrow\;\; v_{c} = 3 b.
$$
Substitute $v_{c} = 3 b$ into the first derivative condition to find $T_{c}$:
$$
\frac{R T_{c}}{(3 b - b)^{2}} = \frac{2 a}{(3 b)^{3}}
\;\;\Rightarrow\;\;
\frac{R T_{c}}{4 b^{2}} = \frac{2 a}{27 b^{3}}
\;\;\Rightarrow\;\;
R T_{c} = \frac{8 a}{27 b}
\;\;\Rightarrow\;\;
T_{c} = \frac{8 a}{27 R b}.
$$
Compute $P_{c}$ by substituting $(v_{c}, T_{c})$ into the equation of state:
$$
P_{c} = \frac{R T_{c}}{v_{c} - b} - \frac{a}{v_{c}^{2}}
= \frac{R \left(\frac{8 a}{27 R b}\right)}{3 b - b} - \frac{a}{(3 b)^{2}}
= \frac{\frac{8 a}{27 b}}{2 b} - \frac{a}{9 b^{2}}
= \frac{8 a}{54 b^{2}} - \frac{a}{9 b^{2}}
= \frac{4 a}{27 b^{2}} - \frac{3 a}{27 b^{2}}
= \frac{a}{27 b^{2}}.
$$
Now substitute the given numerical values $a = 10.5 \,\text{L}^{2}\cdot \text{atm} \cdot \text{mol}^{-2}$, $b = 0.0800 \,\text{L} \cdot \text{mol}^{-1}$, and $R = 0.08206 \,\text{L} \cdot \text{atm} \cdot \text{mol}^{-1} \cdot \text{K}^{-1}$:
$$
T_{c} = \frac{8 a}{27 R b}
= \frac{8 \times 10.5}{27 \times 0.08206 \times 0.0800} \,\text{K}
\approx 4.73908 \times 10^{2} \,\text{K}
\;\Rightarrow\; T_{c} \approx 474 \,\text{K} \text{ (three significant figures)},
$$
$$
P_{c} = \frac{a}{27 b^{2}}
= \frac{10.5}{27 \times (0.0800)^{2}} \,\text{atm}
= \frac{10.5}{27 \times 0.006400} \,\text{atm}
\approx 6.0764 \times 10^{1} \,\text{atm}
\;\Rightarrow\; P_{c} \approx 60.8 \,\text{atm} \text{ (three significant figures)}.
$$
Rounded to three significant figures and presented together, the critical temperature (K) and critical pressure (atm) are as follows.
